4. Conclusion and Future Prospect
As described in this progress report, there is a strong com-
petition between the two key sodium battery technologies:
nonaqueous NaâO
and hybrid Naâair batteries. Nonaqueous
NaâO
batteries are safer than hybrid Naâair due to the usage
of organic electrolyte as anolyte and catholyte. Indeed, the reac-
tion of water with metal sodium can be explosive. However,
the use of an organic electrolyte leads to a nonconductive and
insoluble discharge product that deposits in the pores of the
air electrode and progressively covers the active reaction sites
and blocks the O
diffusion pathway. This detrimental pro-
cess increases the overpotentials specifically during charging,
which is accompanied by a reduction of the power density and
worsens the cyclic stability. In addition, organic electrolytes
are more expensive, flammable, and with a certain level of tox-
icity. Most of nonaqueous NaâO
cell required usage of either
pure and dry oxygen or oxygen diffusion membrane which will
also increase the cost of the cell. However, the research in the
area of hybrid Naâair battery is gaining momentum since its
first reports in 2013. The hybrid Naâair cell uses less organic
electrolyte and consumes air as oxygen source thereby imme-
diately reducing the cost, in contrast to aprotic NaâO
cell. In
mixed electrolyte system (aqueous electrolyte and aprotic elec-
trolyte), the formed discharge product is soluble in water thus
diminishing the clogging and electronic conductivity issues
related to organic electrolytes. Unlike nonaqueous NaâO
bat-
tery, hybrid Naâair battery offers several advantages such as

zation, good cyclic stability, and use of ambient air as source
